  <br>
  You ever notice how the &quot;inspectors will work&quot; crowd always state &quot;given a little more time, Saddam would of been disarmed.&quot;  Saddam was supposed to disarm at the end of the first Gulf War.  The U.N. mandated that action.  Here we are, 12 years later, still arguing about it.  And the only reason Iraq marched a few weapons out in front of the world to see in the month preceding the war was because the coalition forces were massing around Iraq.  The &quot;inspectors will work&quot; crowd are fine with the U.S. and Britain having 100,000 or 200,000 of their troops surrounding Iraq, indefinitely, enforcing the weapons ban.  How long do these troops stay in the Middle East?  Who pays for it?  Gee - take a guess.<br>
  The U.N. is a relic of WWII.  Why does a has been like France sit on the security council?  Why not China?  Or Japan? It's high time to change the makeup of the security council.  And if France, or anyone else in the U.N. doesn't like it, force a change, or form another world body organization.  Sadly, NATO is pretty much history too.  The U.S. needs to form alliances with nations who share common interests for the 21st century.  It's clear to me countries like Russia, France, possibly even Germany, have different agendas in the world than that of the U.S.  It's time for the U.S. to re-evaluate our relationship with Germany, with Russia and especially with the French.     <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#6F6F6F>- </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace>NuclearSpace Message Board</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8>Media, Politics & War</a> <font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.com">NuclearSpace Home Page</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.246c<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

